# Comments

Comments document *intent*, *trade-offs*, *constraints*. They never narrate code.

```ts
// BAD — narrates the code
let i = 0;
// Increment i
i += 1;

// BAD — restates the obvious
// Get the user from supabase
const user = await supabase.auth.getUser();

// GOOD — explains why we chose a value
// 24h matches the donor-portal refresh cadence; we deliberately do not invalidate
// on every donation to avoid hammering Supabase during fundraising spikes.
export const revalidate = 86400;

// GOOD — flags a constraint the reader can't see in code
// Stripe's webhook can deliver the same event twice within minutes;
// we de-dupe on stripe_event_id at the DB layer (unique index).
await db.donations.upsert({ where: { stripe_event_id }, ... });
```

Rules:

- If you can delete the comment without losing information that's not already in the code, delete it.
- If the comment says *what* the code does, delete or rewrite it.
- If you need to explain a Stripe quirk, an IRS rule, an accessibility constraint, or a chosen-vs-rejected design path — that's a comment worth keeping.
- Architectural decisions go in `docs/adr/NNNN-<slug>.md`, not in floating comments.
- TODOs include an owner and a tracking issue or date: `// TODO(eran, 2026-09-01): flip ORG.onlineGivingLive once the production Stripe account is verified.`
